Error 500 typically means the video is not supported by your streaming device. Some devices, like Samsung TVs, will be able to play this video with some help, so try using the \"%1$s\" checkbox to play the video. Also most devices that return error 500 are not capable of playing M3U8 videos, so you should try to stick to MP4 videos.
"Error 500 can also mean your streaming device is denying the connection, make sure your %1$s doesn't have your phone on the list of blocked devices under the TV setting."

To access the subtitle configuration just use the subtitles button on the toolbar of the playback control screen. You have 3 options for using subtitles.

1.- The first and best choice is to let the app use the subtitles from the web page. This is only possible when the subtitles are present, detectable, compatible with your streaming device, and the app can download them. Sometimes it helps if you play the video inside the web page and enable the subtitles on the video on the web page.
"2.- This application also has free integration with OpenSubtitles.com, all you have to do is signup for free at OpenSubtitles.com and then you'll be able to find most subtitles."
3.- You can also use your own subtitle files if you have them. SRT and VTT formats are the only formats supported. On DLNA devices only SRT is supported.

"4.- If your streaming device doesn't support subtitles but has a web browser then give the Web Browser Receiver a try, as it often supports subtitles on devices that don't support them over their traditional protocol, for example, Xbox doesn't support subtitles over DLNA but it does on the web browser."
Subtitles work on streaming devices that support them. Chromecast, Fire TV, and WebOS 2+ support subtitles. Some DLNA streaming devices also support subtitles.

"Typically this means the video is on a format that your streaming device doesn't understand. This can happen if the video is of type M3U8 and your streaming device doesn't support that format. This can also happen if your TV needs some assistance playing the video, in that case you should try using the \"%1$s\" checkbox. This will also happen if casting to a Chromecast and using a TS or AVI video as those formats aren't supported by the Chromecast. Chromecast can also have issues with MKV videos."
